ssumption readers may have about the archive as a neutral library space or about the archival document as a simple and pure text is challenged. In essays discussing celebrated Canadian authors such as Marian Engel and L.M. Montgomery, as well as lesser-known writers such as Constance Kerr Sissons and Marie Rose Smith, Working in Women’s Archives persuades us that our research methods must be revised and refined in order to create a scholarly place for a greater variety of archival subjects and to accurately represent them in current feminist and poststructuralist theories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen authors, CanadianvArchives. 0aWomen authors, CanadianxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 4aArchival Studies. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLife Writing. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBuss, Helen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuss, Helen M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavies, Gwendolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerson, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKadar, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, Rosalind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubio, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerduyn, Christl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920871140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208711423Coveruhttps://www.de